      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm trying to build this tool for my security project to detect ddos by looking at the entropy of ip addresses in our logs. i need a function that takes a list of strings (the ips) and returns the shannon entropy. \n\ni'm having some annoying issues with floating point precision and rounding when i run my tests, so can u make sure it handles that? here is the test i need it to pass:\n\n```python\nimport math\n\ndef test_entropy():\n    # sample logs (representing a mix of normal and some repeated traffic)\n    log_data = [\"192.168.1.1\", \"192.168.1.2\", \"192.168.1.1\", \"10.0.0.5\", \"192.168.1.2\", \"192.168.1.1\"]\n    \n    # the entropy for this specific distribution should be approx 1.459\n    result = calculate_entropy(log_data)\n    \n    # my test expects it to be rounded to 3 decimal places\n    assert round(result, 3) == 1.459, f\"Expected 1.459, but got {round(result, 3)}\"\n    print(\"Test passed!\")\n\ncalculate_entropy([\"192.168.1.1\", \"192.168.1.2\", \"192.168.1.1\", \"10.0.0.5\", \"192.168.1.2\", \"192.168.1.1\"])\ntest_entropy()\n```\n\ncan u write the `calculate_entropy` function for me? it needs to pass that test exactly.",
